<div id=3D"anova-two-way-analysis-of-variance" class=3D"section level2" num=
ber=3D"1.15">
<h2><span class=3D"header-section-number">1.15</span> ANOVA: Two-way
analysis of variance</h2>
<p>This method is appropriate for an ANOVA with two categorical factors
(independent variables). One of these must be a binary factor reflecting
the treatment versus control contrast. The method requires knowledge of
the means in the treatment and control conditions (the marginal means)
and the mean square error. Typically, if this information is provided,
so are the standard deviations and the canonical method can be used.
However, in a case where the standard deviations are not reported, this
method will recover the standardized mean difference effect size. There
is an option for including or excluding the variability associated with
the non-treatment contrast factor into the pooled within groups standard
deviation. You would want to do this if the non-treatment contrast
factor was a characteristic of the participants, such as risk-level or
gender. You would likely not want to do this if the non-treatment
contrast factor was a manipulated factor (experimental), although that
may depend on context. The default is to include this variability. In
the equations below, <span class=3D"math inline"><span class=3D"MathJax_Pre=
view" style=3D"color: inherit;"><span class=3D"MJXp-math" id=3D"MJXp-Span-2=
208"><span class=3D"MJXp-mi MJXp-italic" id=3D"MJXp-Span-2209">A</span></sp=
an></span></span> indicates
the treatment vs.&nbsp;control factor and <span class=3D"math inline"><span=
 class=3D"MathJax_Preview" style=3D"color: inherit;"><span class=3D"MJXp-ma=
th" id=3D"MJXp-Span-2210"><span class=3D"MJXp-mi MJXp-italic" id=3D"MJXp-Sp=
an-2211">B</span></span></span></span> indicates the other factor.</p>
