<div id=3D"binary-dependent-variable-a-2-by-2-frequency-table" class=3D"sec=
tion level2" number=3D"1.16">
<h2><span class=3D"header-section-number">1.16</span> Binary dependent
variable: a 2-by-2 frequency table</h2>
<p>Three different methods are provided below for estimating a
standardized mean difference effect size from a binary dependent
variable. All three produce similar results in most
situations=E2=80=94differences between methods increase as the event rate
approaches 0 or 1. The first two (designated as the logit and the Cox
logit methods) are based on a conversion of the logged odds ratio. The
logic of this is based on the similarity of the logistic and
standardized normal distributions. The former has a mean of zero and a
standard deviation of <span class=3D"math inline"><span class=3D"MathJax_Pr=
eview" style=3D"color: inherit;"><span class=3D"MJXp-math" id=3D"MJXp-Span-=
2550"><span class=3D"MJXp-mi MJXp-italic" id=3D"MJXp-Span-2551">=CF=80</spa=
n><span class=3D"MJXp-mrow" id=3D"MJXp-Span-2552"><span class=3D"MJXp-mo" i=
d=3D"MJXp-Span-2553" style=3D"margin-left: 0.111em; margin-right: 0.111em;"=
>/</span></span><span class=3D"MJXp-msqrt" id=3D"MJXp-Span-2554"><span clas=
s=3D"MJXp-surd"><span style=3D"font-size: 134%; margin-top: 0.104em;">=E2=
=88=9A</span></span><span class=3D"MJXp-root"><span class=3D"MJXp-rule" sty=
le=3D"border-top: 0.08em solid;"></span><span class=3D"MJXp-box"><span clas=
s=3D"MJXp-mn" id=3D"MJXp-Span-2555">3</span></span></span></span></span></s=
pan></span>, whereas the latter has a mean of zero and a standard
deviation of 1. The shapes are similar but not identical, with the
logistic distribution being somewhat leptokurtic. The logit method
simply re-scales the logged odds ratio based on the difference between
the standard deviations for these two distributions. The Cox method
tweaks the conversion to account for the leptokurtic nature of the
logistic distribution, improving the performance of the conversion when
the event rate approaches 0 or 1. The probit method is based entirely on
the normal distribution. This approach finds the <span class=3D"math inline=
"><span class=3D"MathJax_Preview" style=3D"color: inherit;"><span class=3D"=
MJXp-math" id=3D"MJXp-Span-2556"><span class=3D"MJXp-mi MJXp-italic" id=3D"=
MJXp-Span-2557">z</span></span></span></span> associated with the area unde=
r the left
portion of the curve that equals the proportion experiencing the event
for each group. For example, a success rate (or failure rate) of .50
would correspond with a <span class=3D"math inline"><span class=3D"MathJax_=
Preview" style=3D"color: inherit;"><span class=3D"MJXp-math" id=3D"MJXp-Spa=
n-2558"><span class=3D"MJXp-mi MJXp-italic" id=3D"MJXp-Span-2559">z</span><=
/span></span></span> of 0
(half of the distribution is to the left of 0). Similarly, a success
rate of .025 would correspond to a <span class=3D"math inline"><span class=
=3D"MathJax_Preview" style=3D"color: inherit;"><span class=3D"MJXp-math" id=
=3D"MJXp-Span-2560"><span class=3D"MJXp-mi MJXp-italic" id=3D"MJXp-Span-256=
1">z</span></span></span></span> of -1.96. This value is called the
probit of a proportion. The standardized mean difference effect size is
computed as the difference between these two probits. Each of these
methods has a specific equation for its standard error and variance.</p>
