ath" id=3D"MJXp-Span-5691"><span class=3D"MJXp-mi MJXp-italic" id=3D"MJXp-S=
pan-5692">p</span></span></span></span>-value and associated degrees of fre=
edom
can be determined using the inverse probability distribution for the
chi-square. This method uses a Javascript function for this written by
John C. Pezzullo. You can reproduce these result using the functions
built into R, Stata, SPSS, or Excel, as shown below.</p>
<pre><code>* R: qchisq(1-p,df)
* Stata: invchi2(df,1-p)
* SPSS: idf.ch2(1-p,df)
* Excel: CHISQ.INV(1-p,df)</code></pre>
<p>A chi-square from a 2-by-2 frequency table will always have 1 degree
of freedom. This method determines the chi-square from the <span class=3D"m=
ath inline"><span class=3D"MathJax_Preview" style=3D"color: inherit;"><span=
